  "text": "The Kubernetes RBAC authorization system is comprehensively implemented across multiple Go source files in the kubernetes/kubernetes repository. Here are the key components:\n\n## Core Authorization Engine\n\n**RBACAuthorizer** (plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/rbac.go) - The main authorizer implementing the authorizer.Authorizer interface. It contains the Authorize method that evaluates whether a request should be allowed based on RBAC rules. The authorizer uses a RequestToRuleMapper interface to resolve policy rules for users and namespaces. It implements a visitor pattern through authorizingVisitor to evaluate rules against request attributes.\n\n## Rule Resolution and Policy Evaluation\n\n**DefaultRuleResolver** (pkg/registry/rbac/validation/rule.go) - Implements comprehensive rule resolution for RBAC. It provides:\n- RulesFor() method that accumulates all applicable policy rules for a user in a namespace\n- VisitRulesFor() method that iterates through all applicable rules by visiting cluster-wide and namespace-scoped role bindings\n- GetRoleReferenceRules() method that resolves Role or ClusterRole references from RoleBindings/ClusterRoleBindings\n- Supports matching users against various subject types (Users, Groups, ServiceAccounts)\n\n## Subject Access Evaluation\n\n**SubjectAccessEvaluator** (plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/subject_locator.go) - Implements the SubjectLocator interface to determine which subjects are allowed to perform specific actions. The AllowedSubjects() method returns all subjects (users, groups, service accounts) that can perform a given action by examining applicable RoleBindings and ClusterRoleBindings.\n\n## REST API Handler\n\n**SubjectAccessReview REST Handler** (pkg/registry/authorization/subjectaccessreview/rest.go) - Handles SubjectAccessReview API requests. The REST struct with Create() method evaluates whether a user can perform an action and returns the decision status. It converts SubjectAccessReview specifications into authorization attributes and delegates to the authorizer for evaluation.\n\n## Bootstrap RBAC Policies\n\nBootstrap policy definitions are defined in plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/bootstrappolicy/:\n- **policy.go** - Defines cluster-wide roles and role bindings including system roles (cluster-admin, system:nodes, etc.) and component roles (kube-controller-manager, kube-scheduler, etc.)\n- **controller_policy.go** - Defines roles for Kubernetes controllers (replication controller manager, daemon set controller, etc.)\n- **namespace_policy.go** - Defines namespace-scoped roles for system namespaces\n\nThese bootstrap policies are reconciled with the cluster in **pkg/registry/rbac/rest/storage_rbac.go** through the EnsureRBACPolicy() function which creates or updates bootstrap roles and role bindings.\n\n## Privilege Escalation Prevention\n\nPrivilege escalation is prevented through multiple policy-based storage implementations:\n\n**Role Storage** (pkg/registry/rbac/role/policybased/storage.go) - Wraps the standard storage for Roles with escalation checks. Create and Update methods verify that users cannot create/modify roles with permissions they don't already possess.\n\n**ClusterRole Storage** (pkg/registry/rbac/clusterrole/policybased/storage.go) - Similar escalation prevention for ClusterRoles with additional checks for aggregation rules which require cluster-admin privileges.\n\n**RoleBinding Storage** (pkg/registry/rbac/rolebinding/policybased/storage.go) - Prevents users from binding roles they're not authorized to use by verifying users have the \"bind\" privilege on the target role.\n\n**ClusterRoleBinding Storage** (pkg/registry/rbac/clusterrolebinding/policybased/storage.go) - Cluster-wide equivalent of role binding privilege escalation prevention.\n\n**Escalation Check Functions** (pkg/registry/rbac/escalation_check.go) - Provides utility functions:\n- EscalationAllowed() - Checks if user is in system:masters group\n- RoleEscalationAuthorized() - Verifies user has explicit \"escalate\" permission on roles\n- BindingAuthorized() - Checks if user has \"bind\" permission for the referenced role\n- ConfirmNoEscalation() - Core validation that ensures user doesn't grant permissions they don't possess\n\nThe escalation prevention is implemented by having the policy-based storage layers call ConfirmNoEscalation() through the AuthorizationRuleResolver, comparing rules the user is trying to create against the rules they currently possess, denying creation if it would escalate privileges."
